        "sear_text": "Far more than just a prison memoir, this book is infused with the Drukpa Kagyu master Adeu Rinpoche's remarkable compassionate response to the hardship he and others endured and how the realization of the nature of mind can help you overcome all obstacles. It is an inspirational book rich in spiritual realization, pith instructions, and human dignity in the face of adversity.\n\nThe first part of this book includes teachings given by Rinpoche to a group of Western students and is full of pithy advice on Dzogchen and Mahamudra teachings. The second part concerns his time in prison.\n\nThis work offers a portrait of the life and philosophy of one of the twentieth century's most respected meditation masters - his early training in spiritual practices, his flight and capture, interrogation and sentencing, and the years in prison. His voice is calm and nonjudgemental, uplifting the reader with his compassion for his captors.The title, Freedom in Bondage, captures the author's inner liberation in a dire situation.\n\nAdeu Rinpoche's life was extraordinary from the beginning. He was recognized by an incarnation of the previous Adeu Rinpoche and enthroned at the age of seven. As a child and teenager he mastered writing, calligraphy, poetry, astrology, mandala painting, prayer, and meditation. Then, in 1958 at the age of 27, his monastery was attacked and all sacred texts and statues were completely destroyed by the invading Chinese as part of the Cultural Revolution. Sentenced to 15 years in prison for his religious beliefs, Adeu Rinpoche was sent to a remote labour camp, where he watched many of his friends die under the harsh conditions. But imprisonment had an unexpected blessing: he met many accomplished masters, including the late Khenpo Munsel, and learned many practices from them.",
